and to kind of think of them numerically.

128
00:07:19,130 --> 00:07:23,560
So that you can treat them numerically,
you can calculate things like averages.

129
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:26,770
So for example, if you take, in my example
data set,

130
00:07:26,770 --> 00:07:30,630
I asked the students whether or not they
played varsity sports in high school,

131
00:07:30,630 --> 00:07:34,010
that's a binary variable, a yes/no
variable.

132
00:07:34,010 --> 00:07:38,190
If I code that in my data set rather than
coding it as no and yes, if I code that

133
00:07:38,190 --> 00:07:43,660
as 0 for no and 1 for yes, and I actually
think about those 0s and 1s as numbers.

134
00:07:43,660 --> 00:07:47,426
I can in fact calculate an average for
this binary variable.

135
00:07:47,426 --> 00:07:53,398
So again, here is the histogram for,
played varsity sports in high school.

136
00:07:53,398 --> 00:07:58,470
30 or 60% of my sample had played varsity
sports, 40% had not.

137
00:07:58,470 --> 00:08:01,294
What if you thought of that as a series of
0s and

138
00:08:01,294 --> 00:08:03,430
1s, how would you calculate the average?

139
00:08:05,220 --> 00:08:06,010
So let's do that.

140
00:08:06,010 --> 00:08:07,300
How would I calculate the average here?

141
00:08:07,300 --> 00:08:12,802
Well, I've got 20 people who have a value
of 0, 30 people who have a value of 1.

142
00:08:12,802 --> 00:08:15,976
So I'm just literally going to add up
those 30 1s and

143
00:08:15,976 --> 00:08:19,020
those 20 0s, which just gives me a value
of 30, and

144
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:21,564
I'm going to divide by the total number,
which in this case is 50.

145
00:08:21,564 --> 00:08:25,110
So 30 divided by 50 gives me a value of
0.6.

146
00:08:25,110 --> 00:08:30,020
So notice that the average here is just
the percentage of people who answered yes,

147
00:08:30,020 --> 00:08:33,330
the percentage of those who played varsity
sports in high school.

148
00:08:33,330 --> 00:08:38,442
But you can calculate an average, it comes
out to be 60%, 0.6 in this case.

149
00:08:38,442 --> 00:08:42,390
The other way that we tend to

150
00:08:42,390 --> 00:08:47,370
measure central tendency other than the
mean is something called the median.

151
00:08:47,370 --> 00:08:50,750
The median is the exact middle value.

152
00:08:50,750 --> 00:08:54,640
So that means if you were to rank
everybody from the lowest value to

153
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:58,480
the highest value on whatever variable
you're considering, it would be the,

154
00:08:58,480 --> 00:09:01,025
the value that fell right smack in the
middle.

155
00:09:01,025 --> 00:09:04,270
Now, if there are an odd number of
observations, like if

156
00:09:04,270 --> 00:09:09,020
there was 101 observations, then there
will be one value right in the middle.

157
00:09:09,020 --> 00:09:11,970
But actually, if you have an even number
of observations then

158
00:09:11,970 --> 00:09:15,190
there's going to be two values that are
smack in the middle.

159
00:09:15,190 --> 00:09:18,670
So what we do in that case is we take
those two values and we just average them.

160
00:09:18,670 --> 00:09:21,180
We add them up and divide by 2.

161
00:09:21,180 --> 00:09:24,170
So let me give you an example of how we
calculate the median.

162
00:09:24,170 --> 00:09:29,560
So, from this hypothetical data set on
ages of participants to,

163
00:09:29,560 --> 00:09:30,990
in order to calculate the median,

164
00:09:30,990 --> 00:09:36,540
I have to line up the ages from the lowest
17 to the highest 38 which I've done here.

165
00:09:36,540 --> 00:09:39,300
And then, I have an even number of
observations, so

166
00:09:39,300 --> 00:09:40,930
I'm going to have two middle values.

167
00:09:40,930 --> 00:09:43,972
So I'm going to take those two middle
values, 22 and 23, and

168
00:09:43,972 --> 00:09:45,150
I'm going to average them.

169
00:09:45,150 --> 00:09:46,910
Just add them up and divide by 2.

170
00:09:46,910 --> 00:09:49,740
So my median occurs at 22.5.

171
00:09:49,740 --> 00:09:56,142
That means, half of my observations are
below 22.5 and half are above 22.5.

172
00:09:56,142 --> 00:10:00,160
So if 22.5 is here, four observations are
below, four are above.

173
00:10:00,160 --> 00:10:01,970
Half are below, half are above.

174
00:10:01,970 --> 00:10:02,700
That's the median.

175
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,020
So, for example, what if I asked what's
the median of homework?

176
00:10:08,020 --> 00:10:10,804
So it turns out that the median of
homework in my data set was

177
00:10:10,804 --> 00:10:12,430
10 hours per week.

178
00:10:12,430 --> 00:10:16,320
So that means that half of my students
were doing less than 10 hours per week,

179
00:10:16,320 --> 00:10:19,700
and half of my students were doing more
than 10 hours per week.

180
00:10:19,700 --> 00:10:23,330
If you think of this again as masses,
those bars as masses,

181
00:10:23,330 --> 00:10:29,002
that means 50% of the mass is below 10 and
50% of the mass is above 10.

182
00:10:29,002 --> 00:10:33,670
For alcohol drinking, the median turned
out to be 2.0 drinks per week.

183
00:10:33,670 --> 00:10:36,700
So, half of my students had less than two
drinks per week,

184
00:10:36,700 --> 00:10:39,320
half had more than two drinks per week.

185
00:10:40,950 --> 00:10:46,640
And, unlike the mean, the median is not
affected by extreme values.

186
00:10:46,640 --> 00:10:50,620
So, because we're just talking about where
50% are above and

187
00:10:50,620 --> 00:10:54,350
below, it doesn't matter if there are
extreme values in there.

188
00:10:54,350 --> 00:10:58,600
It doesn't matter if in the top 50%,
somebody has a really high level of

189
00:10:58,600 --> 00:11:01,980
drinking or whether the high, the highest
